<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 93 / AEEU points to Germany as role model
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH industry needs legally-based works councils on the German model, the
AEEU engineering and electrical union has told the House of Commons
employment committee inquiry into the future of trade unions.
The country's largest manufacturing union, in a written submission, said
greater worker involvement in running companies would help Britain compete
effectively in world markets.
'If more British companies are to be world class, it is vital that unions
become part of a wider progressive partnership. In Germany, unions play a
constructive, leading role in the works council system and British unions
would almost certainly do the same.'
The unions' 'negative confrontational history' should be discarded in favour
of a more positive, partnership approach. 'The right to independent employee
representation within the workplace should be embodied in law. This would be
a real test of how representative unions are where it matters most - at the
place of work.'
The concept of employee representation should be apolitical rather than at
the whim of a change of government. 'The present government's approach to
individual rights at work is meaningless without access to employee
representation in order that these rights may be pursued. The right to join
a union is of little use unless recognition is guaranteed.'
World class companies 'unlike the British government' see good wages and
conditions, together with a constructive dialogue with employee
representatives, as 'integral to, rather than contrary to, corporate
success'.
There was praise for the industrial relations systems in Germany, Japan and
Sweden - countries with the 'best long-term trading records in manufactured
goods that have well developed employee representation systems'.
The AEEU drew particular attention to the merits of the Rover agreement
signed by the unions last year.
</TEXT>
