<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 93 / Mercury wins government phone contract
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MERCURY Communications, the main domestic competitor to British Telecom, has
won the contract to manage the government's long distance telecommunications
network.
The network, tendered as part of the government's contracting-out programme,
is one of the largest private telecoms networks in the UK, serving about
250,000 civil servants in 550 government offices across the country.
Mercury won the contract against strong competition from Telstra, the
Australian state-owned operator, which recently gained a government licence
to operate in the UK. Both BT and Sprint, the US carrier, withdrew at an
early stage.
The contract, for five years from next April, is for services including
telephone, video-conferencing and mobile communications. The government
network links offices of central government departments across the country,
as well as a range of defence, health, education and security services
institutions.
The contract, which generated revenue equivalent to Pounds 13.5m last year,
is significant for Mercury, a subsidiary of the UK group Cable and Wireless.
Its other large contracts include the Trustee Savings Bank, General Electric
Company and Sedgwick Group, the insurance brokers.
Mr Mike Harris, Mercury's chief executive, said: 'Our understanding of
government requirements, outsourcing expertise and breadth of communications
services will ensure that central government has access to the latest
telecommunications solutions, offering value for money.'
Mr Graham Markey, Telstra's UK director, said he believed Mercury had won
the contract largely on price. 'But we intend to look for other
opportunities in the UK, and are keen to build up our offshore business,' he
said.
Telstra faces strong competition in Australia from Optus, a newly-licensed
operator which is also part-owned by Cable and Wireless.
