<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 93 / Greater financial freedom for Railtrack called for
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FREEDOM from Treasury controls over public expenditure is essential if rail
privatisation is to succeed, according to Mr Bob Horton, chairman of
Railtrack, the organisation that will run the rail infrastructure from April
1994, John Willman writes.
Mr Horton told a Conservative party conference fringe meeting that Railtrack
planned to act as much as possible like a 'commercially-driven plc' and
would require greater freedom from the rigid financial limits that apply to
nationalised industries.
He hoped to attract private investment and would have to develop a
longer-term investment strategy than is possible under the Treasury's
three-year public expenditure planning programme.
