<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 93 / Ford accused of distorting market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORD came under heavy attack yesterday from the leading UK car dealer
association for 'forcing registrations' and 'distorting' the true state of
the market.
It came as figures were released showing that UK new car sales jumped by
11.7 per cent in September.
In one of the most outspoken attacks ever launched by retail dealers against
the car manufacturers, Mr Alan Pulham, director of the national franchised
dealers association claimed that 'the continuing practice by Ford of forcing
registrations distorts the true market situation and has an adverse effect
on prices and residual values'.
The association represents UK dealers selling around 80 per cent of all new
cars and includes most Ford dealers.
The retail motor industry has become increasingly concerned that the strong
rise in new car registrations could mislead the Government 'into thinking
that the car sales revival is more substantial than it in fact is'. Mr
Pullen added: 'The Autumn Budget must not increase taxes - such a move would
severely damage our fragile revival.'
The increase in new car sales in September followed the 17.8 per cent jump
year-on-year of registrations in August, the key new car sales month, which
now accounts for close to a quarter of annual UK new car sales.
According to figures released yesterday by the Society of Motor
Manufacturers and Traders, new car registrations in September rose to
136,100 from 121,823 in the same month a year ago.
New car registrations in the first nine months of the year rose by 11.8 per
cent to 1,450,717 from 1,297,423 in the corresponding period in 1992.
Ford, the UK market leader, reacted angrily to the attack from the retail
dealers.
'We flatly deny that Ford has taken any action to distort the market,' it
said. 'The surge in registrations at the end of September is nothing
unusual. The late strengthening of the market at the end of the month is a
common feature in the UK market.'
Ford said that 27.3 per cent of new car registrations occurred at the end of
September. It claimed that some 38.3 per cent of its registrations took
place in the last five days of September, compared with 17.1 per cent for
Vauxhall, 28.7 per cent for Rover, 39.5 per cent for Peugeot, 35.7 per cent
for Nissan, 38 per cent for Renault, 40.3 per cent for Fiat, 42.6 per cent
for Citroen and 49.5 per cent for Toyota.
Nearly all the major manufacturers had dealer and customer incentive
programmes during the third quarter, said Ford, and many of these finished
at the end of September.
The US car maker offered dealers bonuses of Pounds 100-Pounds 150 per car
for every Escort and Fiesta registered before the end of September.
The franchised dealers association, which is part of the Retail Motor
Industry Federation, claimed that the pre-registering of cars by dealers or
carmakers before the vehicles had actually been sold was 'a major problem
forcing unreality into the market'.
Despite Ford's denials Mr Pulham alleged yesterday that 'Ford, and its
dealers under Ford direction, are pre-registering cars rather than selling
and registering at the same time. Theoretically the two events should be
linked. Unfortunately success is judged by market share.
'If you wish to promote your market share you increase your registrations
but not necessarily your sales on the same day.
'Somebody, either Ford or a dealer, will register a car in September, which
will then be sold in October or later. It will sit in stock with a tax disc
and an L-registration plate, and a customer will be encouraged to buy it as
a nearly-new car.'
Mr Pulham said that 'every manufacturer of any stature plays this game to
some extent and has done for many years. What we have here is an
exceptionally high level of forced sales'.
Mr Pulham claimed that 'this forcing of the market creates the nearly new
car, which then deflects the buyer from the new car market to the
nearly-new. The recovery could easily peter out'.
Mr Roger King, director of public affairs for the Society of Motor
Manufacturers and Traders said: 'The motor industry is building from a very
low base and, coupled with declining export business to EC countries, true
recovery still seems a long way off.'
