<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 93 / MoD official reveals details of secret unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SENIOR Ministry of Defence official yesterday gave details to the Scott
inquiry of a previously highly secretive Whitehall committee which was set
up to control intelligence on sensitive defence exports to Iraq.
According to documents made available to the Scott inquiry, the committee
handled highly sensitive information relating to defence exports that the
inquiry wishes to see.
Mr Ian McDonald, head of the MoD's Defence Exports Services Secretariat, was
asked what he knew about the Restricted Enforcement Unit which was set up in
1987 to supervise intelligence flowing between government departments.
He said he had set up the unit together with Mr Eric Beston, a senior
official at the Department of Trade and Industry, who ran the export
licensing system. The unit was intended to 'supplement' rather than to 'take
the place' of other Whitehall committees, he said.
'We thought it would be a good idea to have a small group of people who knew
each other, who had worked with each other, and who could share information
without letting it spread,' Mr McDonald told the inquiry.
The unit - drawn from Customs and Excise, and members of M15 and its sister
intelligence agency SIS - consisted of 15 to 20 people. Information was
discussed in sessions restricted to few people and in premises that had been
'swept for bugs', Mr McDonald said.
The existence of the unit first became known publicly during the trial last
year of three executives of Matrix-Churchill, the Midlands-based machine
tools manufacturer.
Copies of minutes of the unit's meetings carrying Whitehall's security
classification 'secret - UK eyes only' were released only after a judge
overruled an attempt by government ministers to suppress the documents on
grounds of national interest.
Mr McDonald is due to give further evidence to the inquiry today.
</TEXT>
