<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 93 / CAA chief attacks airline subsidies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CIVIL Aviation Authority yesterday opposed calls for more state aid for
financially-troubled European airlines, adding its voice to the growing
debate over government subsidies for the industry.
Mr Christopher Chataway, CAA chairman, said state subsidies were against the
consumer's interest and threatened to undermine the European Commission's
'open skies' policy.
A committee of EC 'wise men' is investigating the problems facing the
industry and is expected to make recommendations by the end of this year.
The UK is fighting against proposals from other European countries,
including France and Belgium, to provide EC funds to assist airlines in the
recession, as well as a temporary freeze on capacity and fares. Mr John
MacGregor, transport secretary, has also attacked efforts by some EC member
countries to re-regulate the European aviation market.
Sir Colin Marshall, British Airways chairman, recently told the wise men
that restructuring should be allowed to proceed so that airlines can either
improve efficiency and competitiveness or, if they fail, go out of business.
'Clearly some further transitional help is going to be given to some
airlines who are faced with the need to make big cost reductions,' Mr
Chataway said. 'What is important is to ensure that any further short term
aid has only a short term effect.'
Strict conditions and limitations should be introduced to ensure that any
state support to an airline did not distort the longer term future of EC
aviation, he said.
The liberalisation of the market had already yielded some tangible, though
limited, results and had acted as an incentive to many airlines to reduce
costs, Mr Chataway argued. The EC reforms, in the longer term, would help
stimulate competition. But this would not happen if subsidies were allowed
to distort the market.
Even when Europe emerged from its longest post-war recession, Mr Chataway
believed any increase in competition was unlikely to be on a comparable
scale with what occurred after airline deregulation in the US.
</TEXT>
