<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 93 / The Conservative Party Conference: Patten hails opt-out
schools
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN and JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN PATTEN, the education secretary, forecast that well over half the
secondary schools in England and Wales would have attained grant maintained
status by the next general election.
It would prove to be 'an irreversible change,' he told the conference.
Mr Patten announced that from the start of 1994 votes by governing bodies to
determine whether schools should become grant maintained - and escape
control of local education authorities - would be conducted by secret
ballot.
To applause, he said this would would 'clip the wings' of leftwing elements.
Mr Patten said there were over 1,000 grant maintained schools providing the
quality of education that had been a feature of the old grammar and direct
grant schools.
So far, 983 English schools - and about 1,007 in the UK as a whole - have
voted to opt out. There are more than 30,000 state schools in the UK, of
which 4,700 are secondary schools.
Laughter mingled with applause when Mr Patten contrasted the action of Mr
Nigel de Gruchy, general secretary of the NAS/UWT, in sending his son to a
grant maintained school while leading his union's opposition to their
creation.
But Mr de Gruchy fiercely rebutted Mr Patten's speech. He said later:
'Accusations that I support grant-maintained schools are absurd. When my
son's school contemplated grant-maintained status, I attended the parents'
consultative meeting and spoke strongly against it. I voted against it in
the secret parental ballot. Personal attacks based upon misrepresentation of
the truth are no substitute for a convincing educational policy.'
Mr Patten apologised yesterday for calling the chief education officer at
Birmingham City Council a 'nutter' and a 'madman'.
Mr Patten had told a fringe meeting that Professor Tim Brighouse, who took
up his post in Birmingham last month, was a liability.
Prof Brighouse said yesterday he was considering what action to take.
Mr Patten said his comments were 'satirical' but he apologised if they had
caused offence.
</TEXT>
