<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 93 / The Conservative Party Conference: Howard aims to curb
'tidal wave' of crime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Michael Howard, the home secretary, yesterday announced 27 law and order
initiatives to combat 'a tidal wave of concern about crime'.
He won a standing ovation for a tough speech promising to provide extra
prisons, extend police powers, tighten bail provisions and crack down on
young offenders.
The package met many of the demands from angry representatives speaking from
the floor. However, the debate suggested that party activists are unlikely
to be satisfied.
The biggest ovation went to Mr Andrew Rosindell, the Young Conservatives'
chairman, for demanding the return of hanging and birching.
Lord Archer, the novelist and former Conservative MP, also won a standing
ovation for a rousing speech which was widely seen as a bid to replace Sir
Norman Fowler as party chairman.
Mr Howard's first conference speech as home secretary said the balance of
the criminal justice system had tilted too far in favour of criminals.
He said the government would accept many of the 352 recommendations of Lord
Runciman's Royal Commission into criminal justice.
However, he said no decision had been made on Lord Runciman's suggestion
that defendants should lose the right to elect trial by jury.
The main measures announced were:
Right to silence: suspects retain the right not to answer police questions,
but prosecutors may invite judges and juries to infer guilt.
Policing: part-time rural parish constables; powers to stop trespassers
disrupting country sports; less paperwork to release officers for frontline
duties.
Terrorism: tougher stop and search powers; offences of gathering information
for terrorist purposes and reasonable suspicion of connection with terrorist
activities.
Prisons: four new private sector prisons - in addition to two already
announced; crack down on drug use by testing of prisoners.
Court procedures: relaxation of restrictions on use of DNA samples; faster
eviction for squatters; abolition of warnings by rape trial judges on
truthfulness of victims; ban on jury service by offenders on bail.
Juries: new offence of witness intimidation; retrials where juries have been
'nobbled'.
Bail and cautions: end to repeat cautioning; conditions on police bail;
arrest breaches of police bail; end to presumption in favour of bail for
suspects accused of offences while on bail; power to revoke bail; automatic
custody for convicted rapists and murderers accused of reoffending.
Young offenders: doubled maximum sentence for 15-year-olds; secure training
centres for 12- to 14-year-olds; review of community sentencing toughness.
Victims: accept 11 recommendations of royal commission, including
consultation on bail, better information on trial dates and segregation of
offenders and victims.
Sentencing: Criminal Cases Review Authority to look at miscarriages of
justice; extended attorney general's right of appeal against lenient
sentencing.
</TEXT>
