<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 93 / The Conservative Party Conference: Call for move to private
regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MINISTER in charge of the government's deregulation initiative called
yesterday for the 'privatisation' of large sectors of the state's
responsibility for industrial and commercial regulation.
Mr Neil Hamilton, the trade and industry minister, said that industry should
be handed responsibility for setting environmental and product quality
standards and for granting enforcement certificates.
Citing the French example in which fire certification of buildings is
handled by insurance companies, Mr Hamilton said that business would made a
better job of regulation and would inspire greater public trust.
He told a meeting held by the Conservative Way Forward group: 'People would
have more faith in an industry which set standards and which only accredited
those who attained them than they would in a government which seemed
obsessed with minutiae and which paid no regard to what producers could
offer or what the public wanted to receive.'
Mr Hamilton, a prominent member of the right of the Tory party, confirmed
the government's plans to include an 'omnibus' deregulation bill in the next
session of parliament. But in his speech to the Conservative Way Forward he
went much further than the government has hitherto suggested.
In many areas currently regulated by government, compulsion could be
replaced by voluntary incentives similar to the Kite Mark system operated by
the British standards institute, he said.
In others, regulation should simply be scrapped to allow individuals to make
their own choices and trade-offs.
Mr Hamilton concluded: 'Much of what is presently done by regulation does
not need to be done at all. It denies people to make the choices and
trade-offs they want to make. It takes some products and services out of the
reach of customers and denies them their benefits.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
