<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 93 / The Conservative Party Conference: The price of sound
finance - Conference Notebook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT'S the economy, stupid. The Conservative party briefly escaped yesterday
the inexorable logic of US President Bill Clinton's dictum. Criminals,
single mothers, leftwing teachers and social security scroungers are
unmissable targets. Messrs Michael Howard, John Patten and Peter Lilley took
full advantage. They scored one or two bullseyes. Today it is back to
reality.
By all accounts Mr Kenneth Clarke is planning a typically combative speech.
There will be some good news. The recovery may be patchy but Britain's
economy is growing faster than any other in Europe. The fall in inflation is
more than a blip. Manufacturing industry has both a grip on its costs and a
real competitive edge. Lady Thatcher's enterprise culture lives on.
As Mr Stephen Dorrell, one of Mr Clarke's Treasury team, put it yesterday on
the fringe, the prize on the horizon is an end to boom and bust. In the
background other ministers are whispering about the opportunity for an early
cut in interest rates.
All that's needed now, Mr Clarke will tell us, is one more heave to get the
country's public finances in order. That means the toughest public spending
round for a decade or more. The chancellor must keep open also the option of
further measures to raise revenue (the phrase does not sound quite as bad as
tax increases) in the Budget. But what is a Tory government for if it is not
to preside over sound finance. No mention, of course, of how the government
got itself in to this particular mess.
In spite of the threat that the economic debate will be the first in
Blackpool worthy of that description, Mr Clarke cannot afford to backtrack
over the imposition of value added tax on fuel. In retrospect he believes it
was a mistake to prolong the agony by deferring full implementation until
1995. He might yet bring it forward to next April. His only hope is that the
promise of a relatively generous compensation package will contain the anger
among the Tory faithful.
It is a plausible package for a conference which would occasionally like to
forget how divided its party has become. Even Lady Thatcher might allow
herself a supportive smile. Mr Norman Lamont, speaking on the conference
fringe only moments after Mr Clarke has sat down, may not be quite so
forgiving.
For all his natural self-confidence, the chancellor is a worried man. So is
Mr John Major, who spent yesterday afternoon poring over Mr Clarke's text.
Promising sound finance is a lot easier than delivering it. Nor can the
beleagured prime minister afford the luxury of the medium-term perspective
of his chancellor.
Mr Clarke has made two basic promises which provide the fixed points for the
Budget. The first is that he will secure a faster reduction in the borrowing
requirement. The second is that he will not cut public spending to below the
level agreed by the cabinet in July. Only faster economic growth, higher
taxes or both will square that particular circle.
There have been one or two signs that faster growth will provide a partial
lifeline over the medium term. Shrewd observers in Blackpool are suggesting
that the doomsters may be pleasantly surprised. Against that, the latest
smoke-signals from the Treasury suggest that for the current financial year
borrowing may still be close to Pounds 50bn.
For all the jeers from the Tory right it is also clear that the spending
round is turning out to be a great deal tougher than generally realised. Mr
Clarke has referred to blood on the Whitehall carpets. Spending colleagues
say the blood is also on the walls and ceilings.
Mr Clarke will not make up his mind on how much extra revenue he needs until
around the end of this month, although the broad shape of the Budget will be
sketched out at Dorneywood in 10 days time. But the best guess of those who
read his lips is that the chancellor is thinking in terms of a net tax
increase of between Pounds 4bn or Pounds 5bn.
For all his public bravado about extending VAT, there is no certainty that
he will bite that particular bullet. The prospective spending cuts already
threaten Mr Major's fragile Commons majority.
The switch in Budget timing will give restless Tory MPs four months before
the start of the financial year to rebel against VAT on transport, books or
children's clothes. Much safer, Mr Clarke might judge, to raise what he
needs by some clever juggling with income tax allowances.
His combative style and the reflex loyalty of the Tory faithful should
guarantee him a standing ovation for his first conference speech as
chancellor. He should make the most of it. There won't be many plaudits from
Tory voters after November 30.
</TEXT>
<XX>
