<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 93 / IMF reinstates Cambodia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE International Monetary Fund has reinstated Cambodia as a full member and
approved a Dollars 9m (Pounds 5.9m) loan under its Systemic Transformation
Facility, designed to help once centrally planned countries make the leap to
a market economy.
The decision follows pledges from donor countries gathered in Washington
under the chairmanship of France and Japan to pay off Cambodia's Dollars 52m
arrears to the IMF.
Cambodia took advantage of last week's annual meetings of the IMF and World
Bank in Washington to complete negotiations on a Dollars 62.7m emergency
loan from the World Bank, intended to let the country finance essential
imports.
A World Bank mission is due next month to examine the need for
infrastructure investment. But Cambodia's needs present unusual problems
because of years of war.
Reuter adds from Washington: The IMF announced yesterday it would lend
Vietnam about Dollars 223m to help rebuild its economy. Last week Vietnam
made itself eligible for new funding by paying off about Dollars 140m in IMF
arrears for previous loans with the help of a group of wealthy donor
countries, particularly France and Japan.
</TEXT>
