<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 93 / France prepares to reform state-run pension system
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE French government has started to prepare proposals for its long-awaited
reform of the pension system with a view to presenting a legislative package
to parliament next spring.
Mr Edmond Alphandery, economy minister, has formed a working party to
produce provisional proposals for reform of the existing state-controlled
system.
At present the working party is operating on an informal basis. However, Mr
Alphandery hopes to have finalised the details of the package by the end of
the year.
Pension reform is one of the most pressing and complex issues on the French
government's financial agenda.
The system worked well in the 1950s and 1960s when France had a large, young
working population. But it now faces collapse as the population has aged and
a proportionally smaller group of workers struggles to support a growing
number of pensioners.
The simplest solution would be to alleviate the pressure on the state system
by encouraging the French to invest in private pensions. However, previous
governments have baulked from the electorally risky task of persuading the
French to pay extra for their own private pensions while continuing in the
state system.
Mr Alphandery is said to be determined to change the system. His ministry
has already demonstrated an ability to devise original schemes, notably the
'Balladur bond', which raised FFr110bn (Pounds 12.8bn) covered by
privatisation sales of the same amount over the next 18 months.
</TEXT>
<XX>
