<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 93 / Ministers oppose plans for further deep spending cuts:
Rifkind and Lilley resist demands by Treasury to squeeze budgets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FIERCE STRUGGLE has broken out in cabinet over attempts to make deep cuts
in defence and welfare spending as part of the drive to meet public spending
targets for the next three years.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, defence secretary, is demanding a full-scale review of
Britain's armed forces if the Treasury refuses to drop its demands for
further cuts in his budget.
Lady Thatcher last night stepped into the argument by warning against
defence cuts. She told Young Conservatives in Blackpool it was vital for
Britain to maintain a strong defence.
Mr Peter Lilley, the social security secretary, is understood to have
rejected a demand from Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, for radical
reductions in a range of welfare benefits.
Several other departments have been forced already to concede in principle
deep cuts in their budgets for the next three years. But senior Whitehall
officials said the gulf between Mr Rifkind and Mr Lilley on one side of the
argument and the Treasury on the other amounted to billions of pounds.
The transport department's roads programme, the environment department's
housing and urban regeneration budgets and the government's subsidy for
local authorities are emerging as the main victims.
The education and health budget also face a tough squeeze but have so far
escaped the worst of the cuts required to meet a freeze in real terms on
overall spending for the two financial years - 1994-95 to 1995-96. For
1996-97 the plans allow for an inflation-adjusted increase of 1 per cent.
Senior Whitehall officials said the row over defence and social security had
stalled the work of EDX, the cabinet committee charged with sharing out the
spending cake. Until the two departments reached a settlement it would be
impossible to finalise other Whitehall budgets.
Mr Clarke admitted at the weekend that the bargaining in EDX had left 'blood
on the carpet' in Whitehall. Mr Rifkind also alluded to the struggle in a
speech to the Conservatives' Blackpool conference. The defence secretary
warned that the cuts in armed forces spending agreed under the Options for
Change programme following the end of the cold war had left the Pounds 23bn
defence budget at close to its acceptable limit.
Mr Rifkind, who earlier this year was forced into an embarrassing U-turn to
save two threatened army regiments, has told the Treasury the additional
billions it is seeking in savings over the next three years would seriously
undermine Britain's defence strategy.
The cuts could only be implemented after a full-scale re-evaluation of
defence requirements and capabilities. The Treasury, however, is aware such
a review could provoke a political storm in which Conservative backbench MPs
would effectively veto significant spending reductions.
Mr Michael Portillo, chief secretary to the Treasury, has argued that the
cuts are essential to meet the government medium-term spending targets. The
gap between total Whitehall spending bids and the agreed targets is proving
impossible to bridge for 1996-97.
For his part, Mr Lilley has rejected Treasury demands for reductions in his
Pounds 80bn budget going well beyond an agreed clampdown on invalidity
benefit. Among the radical options under discussion in EDX are the
'means-testing' or taxing of child benefit and the transfer to employers of
responsibility for sickness and industrial injury benefits.
Mr Lilley has successfully fought off a suggestion that all benefits should
be frozen rather than uprated in line with inflation next year.
He is also arguing that most of the other cuts demanded by the Treasury
would be defeated by Tory backbench rebellions in the Commons.
