<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 93 / International Company News: Trizec debt move may miss
default deadline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR debenture holders of Trizec, the troubled North American property
group, will continue studying the company's financial restructuring plan for
another two weeks, almost certainly delaying approval beyond October 20.
Trizec, a publicly-held affiliate of the Hees-Edper group of Toronto,
proposed a CDollars 1.86m (USDollars 1.39m)debt and preferred stock
restructuring in August. It sought approval by October 20 to avoid default
on a CDollars 84m Swiss-franc debenture issue due then.
The trustee for the senior debenture holders owed CDollars 1.1bn said
advisers are studying Trizec's legal and financial situation closely to
determine whether the restructuring is acceptable. When they have all the
information needed they will resume negotiations with Trizec.
The company said it was willing to delay the approval meeting beyond October
20 and find means to avoid technical default on the Swiss debenture issue if
necessary.
Trizec's debt, some in bearer form, is held widely in North America and
Europe, making the approval process for the restructuring complex. The
company was caught by the 1991 slump in North American property markets.
The senior debenture holders' steering committee is headed by a
representative of the Union Bank of Switzerland.
</TEXT>
