<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 93 / International Company News: Obayashi in retreat from
property in California
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OBAYASHI, the Japanese construction company, is to withdraw from the US west
coast property market by liquidating three Los Angeles-based subsidiaries
and writing-off losses of Y30bn (Dollars 278m) in the year to March.
The Japanese contractor can apparently afford to bear the losses this year,
as it has avoided the worst of a corruption scandal in which executives from
five other leading construction companies have been arrested in recent weeks
for the alleged bribery of provincial politicians.
Japanese construction companies, hit by the fall in property prices and
orders at home, have been reducing their exposure in the international
market. The scandals in Tokyo have given them another reason to minimise
investment risks.
Companies implicated in the scandal, including Taisei and Hazama, have been
temporarily suspended from bidding for some public works projects, creating
opportunities for Obayashi and other contractors which have so far avoided
the ignominy of arrests.
The government suspensions for contractors implicated in the scandal are
expected to influence private orders received by the companies. Taisei said
yesterday that it had not lost private contracts, but private orders for the
industry are down 30 per cent to 40 per cent because of the depressed
property market.
In spite of a record fall of 40.6 per cent in national and local government
orders received by the largest 50 Japanese contractors in August, Obayashi
said pre-tax profit for the year to March would be Y60bn, up from a
previously forecast Y52bn.
The write-offs arising from the Los Angeles liquidations will cut net profit
to Y13bn from a projected Y23bn, the company said. Sales for the period are
expected to be Y1,600bn, down slightly from the forecast Y1,640bn.
Obayashi will remain active in Hawaii and Europe.
</TEXT>
