<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 93 / International Company News: German exchanges to merge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Frankfurt stock exchange, the largest of Germany's eight stock
exchanges, is to merge with the Deutsche Terminborse, Germany's screen-based
futures and options exchange, at the beginning of next year, the Deutsche
Borse announced yesterday.
This is the first change in the structure of Germany's security markets
since the creation of the Deutsche Borse, the German stock exchange, at the
beginning of the year. This organisation is a holding company which brings
the Frankfurt exchange, the DTB and the Deutscher Kassenverein settlements
organisation under one administrative roof.
The Deutsche Borse said the aim of the merger of the DTB and the Frankfurt
exchange was to integrate the markets for equities and fixed interest
securities with that for options and futures. It would lead to further
meshing of trading and settlement between the two markets, the Deutsche
Borse said.
These changes are administrative in nature and are unlikely to bring
immediate benefits for investors in German securities. However, they are
part of a campaign on the part of the German securities industry to improve
its competitiveness and are likely to presage significant changes.
'These steps are required in order to achieve a considerable improvement in
the competitiveness (of the German securities markets) against other
European markets,' it said. They would lead in time to faster settlement and
lower costs for investors, the Deutsche Borse said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
