<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 93 / International Company News: Office products fall hits J
Crean
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A REDUCED contribution from its office products division meant pre-tax
profits of James Crean, the Dublin-based industrial holding company, slipped
from IPounds 7.78m to IPounds 7.68m (Pounds 7.34m) in the first half of
1993.
Sales grew 8.5 per cent to IPounds 120.9m, while earnings per share edged up
to 12.8p (12.5p) because of the buy-out in January of the minority in Valley
Fresh Foods and a slightly lower tax charge.
An interim dividend of 5.635p (7.865p) is declared but a final of not less
than 6.865p is forecast for a maintained total of 12.5p. The directors have
reiterated their policy of a progressive dividend policy.
Crean blamed a Pounds 1.1m fall to Pounds 600,000 in profits from office
products on adverse market circumstances. Elsewhere, food and beverages
turned in Pounds 5.6m (Pounds 4.8m), Inishtech made Pounds 4m (Pounds 3.7m)
and electrical wholesaling Pounds 600,000 (Pounds 700,000).
Directors said the trading pattern had not changed materially since the end
of June and with the exception of office products, all operating divisions
continued to perform satisfactorily.
Market conditions are expected to remain difficult for the office products
businesses for some time.
The US contributed the bulk of profits with Pounds 5m (Pounds 4.4m), helped
by a more favourable dollar/punt rate. Irish profits were unchanged at
Pounds 1.1m, while the European performance was lower at Pounds 4.7m (Pounds
5.4m).
Group borrowings at June 30 were IPounds 86m, against IPounds 72m at the
same time last year and IPounds 70m at the year end. This represented
gearing of 93 per cent, compared with 77 per cent at the year end.
Profits of TRD Group were included up to the date of disposal in June.
</TEXT>
