<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 93 / The time has come to cut Japan down to size
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Japanese stock market is posing one of its periodical challenges to the
practice of setting performance benchmarks for international equity
portfolios. Tokyo's market capitalisation has bounced back and is once more
threatening to impose its own unrealistic values on global fund managers.
Benchmarks are usually based upon stock market indices, and indeed the
global stock market index series - such as the FT-Actuaries World Index -
were constructed primarily with this purpose in mind. A fund manager's
starting point can therefore be, say, the World ex-US Index, which he must
track or beat.
But once before, in the late 1980s, the Japanese bubble threatened this
approach. At the peak in late 1989 the Tokyo market was worth 45 per cent of
the world market capitalisation. What was worse, it amounted to more than 60
per cent of the global market outside the US, a degree of concentration
which threatened to destroy the whole purpose of international
diversification for US pension funds.
A lesson was learned. If you follow the index-based approach too slavishly
you can wind up overexposed to the overvalued markets and underexposed to
the cheap ones. It was enough to encourage dabbling with alternative
weighting schemes, such as GDP weights. But then, to everyone's relief,
especially to that of western fund managers who were underweight in Tokyo,
the Japanese bubble was deflated.
By mid-1992 the Japanese market was down to a 24 per cent World Index
capitalisation weighting. It was still a bit high for comfort, but was not
wildly out of line with the Japanese share of GDP of the Organisation for
Economic Co-operation and Development area (about 20 per cent).
Given that the Nikkei Dow Average is still at only just over half its peak
level, there the matter might have rested. But in the past year a new bubble
has blown up, this time involving the yen. Unhedged UK investors could have
achieved a return of 60 per cent over the past year, in the unlikely event
of matching the performance of the Tokyo index, and in sterling terms Tokyo
is within 20 per cent of its end-1989 peak.
Thus Tokyo has zoomed back, to represent nearly a third of the world market.
To US eyes, it amounts to half of the non-US capitalisation. To be fully
weighted could be dangerous, but to have been underweight in the past year
has been agonising.
None of this would matter much if Japanese companies were powering ahead.
Then heavy investment in them might look sensible. But many are facing a
currency shock that could prove disastrous and will certainly be
uncomfortable. The average return on equity in manufacturing has collapsed
to about 2 1/2 per cent, and the average p/e ratio for Tokyo stocks is no
longer (as it was in the late 1980s) 40 or even 60 but more like 90.
Here is how the problem appears to UK pension funds. A manager following a
median benchmark will know that the typical exposure of his peer group funds
to overseas equities is 24 per cent. Tokyo represents 35 per cent of the
World ex-UK capitalisation. So about 8 1/2 per cent of his portfolio ought
to be in Japanese equities. However, the actual exposure of UK pension funds
is only half as much. They are strongly angled instead towards continental
European equities where they have nearly 10 per cent of their portfolios
compared with a 'neutral' 4 per cent. Our manager with a median benchmark
can safely stay on half a full Tokyo weighting and not run much of a risk of
performing very differently from his peers. If he had an index-based
benchmark, he would be under greater pressure to adopt the full exposure.
The new Tokyo problem is the result of curious circumstances. In theory,
when a currency soars the domestic stock market will tumble because
profitability is undermined. But Tokyo is underpinned by support from public
pension funds. The optimists see a big jump in profits in 1995 as pay levels
are cut and the Japanese corporate sector starts to shed surplus workers. It
would require a revolution in employer-employee relationships.
How this will work out is the subject of various opinions, but in the
meantime those fund sponsors being pulled by benchmarks into heavy exposures
to the Tokyo market are being braver than perhaps they realise.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
    P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    ECON  Gross domestic product.
</TP>
