<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 93 / CBI chief calls on ministers to end policy 'vacuum'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Howard Davies, director- general of the Confederation of British
Industry, yesterday called on ministers to develop strategies to counter
what he called 'the current vacuum' at the heart of government economic
policy.
He also outlined the areas the CBI would like to see reformed. They will be
included in its new policy document, The Competitiveness of British
Industry: the role of government, to be published next week.
Mr Davies said: 'The government needs a framework of policy guidelines
setting out its industrial strategy. It is no good if the Department of
Trade and Industry produces a new definition of policy if it fails to get
its message across to other departments.'
The CBI's industrial paper outlines seven areas in which it would like to
see significant changes in government policy. These include public
expenditure and taxation, education and training, transport planning, trade
and investment and regulation. 'This should provide the framework for a
restatement of government industrial policy,' Mr Davies said.
He described the present government spending round as a 'ridiculous horse
trade' which inevitably resulted in unsatisfactory decisions. 'It often ends
in government investing in failure instead of investing in success.'
Speaking earlier at a fringe meeting at the Conservative conference in
Blackpool, Mr Davies said nothing short of a new definition of the aims of
government industrial policy would do.
He warned his audience against believing that each government department was
formulating its own policy towards industry. 'That is not adequate to fill
the vacuum at the heart of government economic policy. Businessmen do not
understand the government's objectives.'
Mr Richard Needham, trade minister, replied that manufacturing industry was
crucial to Britain's economic success, but said it would not be politically
sensible for the government to publish its industrial objectives which could
be open to criticism.
</TEXT>
