FT  06 OCT 93 / Plans to tax lottery proceeds attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LOTTERY Promotion Company, backed by eight economists, will next week
attack the government's national lottery plans.
The aim is to 'improve' the Lottery Bill before it receives royal assent
early next month and make sure more of the proceeds go to good causes.
The company has been campaigning for the national lottery, which could be a
Pounds 4bn to Pounds 5bn business, to be a charitable foundation.
Mr Denis Vaughan, the company's executive director, yesterday said: 'Big
business - and the Treasury - are going to make hundreds of millions profit
from a lottery designed for the benefit of the country.'
The company argues against the Treasury imposing a 12 per cent tax on the
lottery's proceeds.
'The economists point out the only reason for a monopoly lottery is to
maximise funding for good causes,' said Mr Vaughan. 'Therefore the lottery
should be untaxed.'
