<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 93 / Tests for video link may cost BT Pounds 75m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Telecommunications is proposing to test its video-on-demand
entertainment service in as many as 250,000 homes next year.
The experiment is expected to cost about Pounds 75m and would probably be
conducted in rural areas such as Suffolk or Sussex.
BT technologists believe pictures of VHS or Super VHS quality can be
delivered down telephone lines to 90 per cent of the 23m homes connected to
the BT network. The digitally compressed pictures which would go through a
special decoder could go down the telephone wire at the same time as a
conversation.
If the experiment succeeds BT would go ahead with the investment of several
billion pounds needed to create a national system.
Recently the Independent Television Commission said it thought that a
video-on-demand service would not need a special licence under broadcasting
legislation.
BT envisages a system where a menu is produced on a television screen and
viewers are able to call up the movie or programme of their choice.
Cable TV, Separate Section
</TEXT>
