<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 93 / Fears over combined heat and power
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RISE of energy-efficient power generation systems could be jeopardised
by sharply higher gas prices to industrial consumers, the Combined Heat and
Power Association warned yesterday.
Mr David Green, its director, said the industry's strong growth in recent
years had been 'kick-started' by British Gas's low-cost interruptible
supplies. Interruptible users pay low prices but risk being cut off at times
of peak demand.
The association fears that moves to enhance competition by forcing British
Gas to give up parts of its non-interruptible market could lead it to raise
interruptible prices.
Mr Green said a 'narrow' focus on competition by the Department of Trade and
Industry in its review of the Monopolies and Mergers Commission report on
the future of British Gas could frustrate government environmental goals to
reduce carbon dioxide emissions.
A government target says CHP systems should account for 5,000MW, or about 8
per cent, of installed capacity by the year 2000. The CHP process produces
both heat and electricity.
</TEXT>
