<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 93 / Acid rain target 'being beaten'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday said the UK was ahead of its international
commitments to reduce acid rain.
It said figures on harmful gas emissions showed that last year's output of
sulphur dioxide and oxides of nitrogen was below the levels established by
the UK plan that implements targets set by the European Community's large
combustion plants directive.
Total emissions were 2.67m tonnes of sulphur dioxide and 701,645 tonnes of
nitrous oxides. Quotas for the year were 3.25m tonnes and 925,000 tonnes
respectively.
Long-term targets aim for a cut of 60 per cent on 1980 sulphur dioxide
levels by the year 2003, and 30 per cent on nitrous oxide levels by 1998.
The emissions cover power generating plants, refineries and other industry.
The UK received more relaxed emission quotas in the directive than other EC
countries because of the large size of its coal-fired power industry, and
the expense of cleaning it.
Much of last year's reduction was due to a fall in the use of coal-fired
power stations. Although two large stations are to add flue gas
desulphurisation equipment, the first of these, at Drax in South Yorkshire,
will not start until the end of this year.
The environmental lobby has criticised the reduction as inadequate, arguing
it is driven by regulation and not ecological necessity. Acid rain is said
to damage plants, animals and buildings. Tougher standards are being
negotiated by industrialised countries, and these are set to be in the
directive next year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
