<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 93 / Howe seeks policy information for case to Iraq probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD HOWE, the former chancellor and foreign secretary, has asked Whitehall
officials to supply documentary evidence of cases in which the government
has withheld information about UK foreign policy from parliament.
Lord Howe's request is related to his appearance, expected next January,
before the Scott arms-to-Iraq inquiry.
Lord Howe's office said yesterday that he was not prepared to make any
comment until he gave evidence to the inquiry.
'His position will become clear then,' a spokesman for Lord Howe said.
It has emerged that in recent weeks that Foreign Office departments have
been asked to broaden their research for current and former ministers
appearing before the Scott inquiry to include diplomacy during the 1980s in
countries other than Iraq.
According to senior Whitehall sources, departments have been asked to find
instances of government policy not being spelt out to parliament on the
grounds that officials and ministers at the time judged this to be in the
overriding public and national interest.
A possible example relates to secret diplomacy with Argentina in the years
after the Falklands war.
Within Whitehall there is a widely held view that officials and ministers
have been put on the defensive by Lord Justice Scott and his counsel Miss
Presiley Baxendale QC and need to put their case across more forcefully in
the coming weeks.
Lord Howe served as foreign secretary between 1983 and 1989. He announced
guidelines restricting arms exports to Iraq and Iran to parliament in
October 1985.
Documents made available to the Scott inquiry show the guidelines had been
secretly agreed to by ministers in December 1984.
Lord Howe's former junior minister at the Foreign Office, Mr William
Waldegrave, told the Scott inquiry last month that they were secretly
relaxed in 1988, but argued that this was a minimal change.
Information given to parliament in 1988 had been misleading. But he argued
that the withholding of information served the public interest because it
protected British hostages held in the Middle East.
The inquiry today takes evidence from Mr Ian McDonald, the head of the MoD
Defence Export Services Secretariat.
</TEXT>
