<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 93 / Ferry port warns Pounds 7m loan vital for development
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PORTSMOUTH'S successful municipal ferry port could be in jeopardy if the
government refuses its request to borrow Pounds 7m for expansion.
The port needs to reclaim land, improve parking, port handling facilities
and increase berths for the new super-ferries, if business is not to be lost
to the trust port of Poole, Southampton and the Channel tunnel.
The improvements would cost Pounds 20m by the end of the decade and Pounds
7m in the financial year 1994-95.
Because the port is owned by the Portsmouth district council it is subject
to constraints on local government spending and cannot borrow funds for
capital spending without government approval.
The port says the Ministry of Transport is cutting municipal ports'
allocation in 1994-95 from Pounds 12m to Pounds 4m. Portsmouth's share would
be Pounds 1m.
About 255,000 freight vehicles a year use the port and the figure is growing
by 20 per cent a year. With just under 3m passengers annually and 810,000
cars, Portsmouth is the second largest passenger terminal in the UK after
Dover.
The port fears that without the expansion its main users Brittany Ferries
and P&amp;O Ferries could move elsewhere.
Rear Admiral Tony George, port manager, said: 'The developments are vital if
we are to expand. The new ferries which are coming on stream are like
hotels. We have also to improve our freight marshalling facilities if the
tunnel is not to take our business.'
The port is scheduled to make an operating surplus of more than Pounds 3m
this year from revenues of Pounds 14m. This goes to the district council and
if the government continues to refuse extra funds, some of it could be used
on the port.
</TEXT>
