<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 93 / Fishermen offer plan to replace time curbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FISHERMEN in England and Wales yesterday proposed measures aimed at
persuading the government to abandon its controversial limits on the number
of days trawlers can spend at sea.
The measures did not include a proposal put forward last week by
representatives of Scotland's 8,000 fishermen that the government should
temporarily abandon the EC system of quotas on the type and quantity of
their catch.
The government has opted to restrict time at sea from next January as part
of its effort to comply with EC rules by cutting the capacity of the UK
fleet by 19 per cent by 1996.
Mr Barrie Deas, secretary of the National Federation of Fishermen's
Organisations, representing 6,000 fishermen in England, Wales, Northern
Ireland and the Channel Islands, said his organisation has put forward some
similar alternative proposals to those of the Scottish fishermen, notably on
increasing the size of mesh in nets and introducing compulsory square mesh
panels which allow young fish to escape.
The NFFO, which will seek judicial review of the limits on days at sea on
November 1, called for increases in minimum landing sizes for fish and
no-fishing zones to protect young and breeding fish.
</TEXT>
