<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 93 / The Conservative Party Conference: Pressure over BR sell-off
reversal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE WERE several strong calls yesterday for the government to reverse its
recent humiliating defeat on a central element of its plans to privatise
British Rail.
But Mr John MacGregor, the transport secretary, stopped short of saying that
the government would try to reverse an amendment to the rail privatisation
bill passed by the House of Lords in July. The amendment seeks to give BR a
greater role in bidding for the new franchises.
In July parliament's upper chamber insisted that BR should be allowed to bid
for rail franchises after privatisation alongside other groups. Proposers of
the amendment argued that BR managers should have an opportunity to bid for
the privatised net-work.
Mr Robin Morris (Morecambe and Lunesdale Conservatives), opening the
transport debate, claimed that the amendment was contrary to the aims of
rail privatisation.
'(The amendment) allows BR, financed by taxpayers' money, to compete against
its own management,' he said.
He claimed that rail restructuring would bring about smaller and more
manageable units and provide new opportunities.
In his speech Mr MacGregor carefully avoided mentioning the Lords'
amendment.
In recent days, ministers have privately acknowledged that it would be
difficult to defeat the amendment in the Commons because it has the support
of some Conservative MPs.
Mr MacGregor confined himself to saying that this matter would be considered
when the House came back from its recess. 'The original bill was right,' he
said.
Mr MacGregor said that the government had given a commitment to the Lords
that it would re-examine the arguments contained in their amendment. But he
was concerned that it might discourage the enthusiasm of BR's regional
managers to bid for franchises.
'There are some 30 management buy-outs in the offing for British rail,' he
said. 'A lot of regional managers are ready to get up and go.'
Touching on road policy in his speech, Mr MacGregor had said that the
government had not yet decided whether to ask motorists to pay more directly
for use of motorways.
But responses to a recent green paper on motorway tolling revealed majority
support among the organisations concerned for some form of charging if it
led to more resources being spent on roads.
He also reported that electronic tolling was much preferred to the
introduction of permits, for which there was little support.
</TEXT>
