FT  06 OCT 93 / The Conservative Party Conference: Lamont's credibility was
undermined, says Clarke
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR KENNETH CLARKE yesterday fuelled tension between himself and Mr Norman
Lamont by asserting bluntly that his predecessor as chancellor had lost all
credibility on economic policy before his removal earlier this year.
Mr Clarke said Mr Lamont had 'got himself into a dreadful situation where
nobody took the slightest notice of anything he said on economic policy.'
'He was subjected to a campaign of continual harassment about his credit
cards and all kinds of irrelevancies by people who presumably thought they
were entitled to do this because they believed he should have resigned after
Black Wednesday.'
Mr Clarke's remarks in the Bow Group magazine Crossbow came just two days
before both men are due to speak at the conference - Mr Clarke in the main
hall and Mr Lamont on the fringe.
Party managers are worried that Mr Lamont may be provoked into launching a
fresh attack on the government's policies after his recent endorsement of
rightwing opposition to tax increases.
Arguing that Mr Lamont was 'entitled to take the credit for the fact that
Britain is now recovering when the rest of Europe is not,' Mr Clarke said
the Pounds 50bn public sector borrowing requirement his predecessor had
bequeathed was a 'big problem.'
