<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 93 / The Conservative Party Conference: Howard floats idea of
limit on benefits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHANGES to the social security system to encourage 'responsibility', such as
limiting welfare benefits after the first child, were floated yesterday by
Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, yesterday.
Speaking to a fringe meeting, Mr Howard highlighted pilot schemes in the US
where, for example, New Jersey had capped the benefits available for second
and later children.
He told the meeting that policies across a range of areas - housing, moral
education at school and adoption law - should be examined to ensure that
they did not provide an incentive for irresponsible behaviour.
Mr Howard said that in addressing the breakdown of discipline and authority
the government must also argue strongly the case for the traditional family
and try to create a spirit of independence in communities badly affected by
crime.
In contrast to some of the messages coming from the Tory party about the
availability of welfare benefits, he said most girls 'probably don't get
pregnant to get a council house or to receive an income from the state' but
he said that for young men 'social security benefits all too often appear as
an entitlement'.
He argued that with few adult role models, children in one-parent families
were more likely to succumb to peer pressure. 'The children, instead of
learning the difference between right and wrong, may instead concentrate on
how not to get caught,' he said.
'And since the state is educating, housing and feeding their children, the
nature of parental responsibility may seem less immediate.'
Far too often, offenders had appeared before the court to receive repeated
conditional discharges and probation orders, Mr Howard said.
Disintegration of what it sees as traditional family values is one of the
issues the party is keen to address. Ministers are committed to ensuring
that so far as possible the welfare state does not provide incentives
towards 'irresponsible behaviour'.
Mr Howard is to give the keynote speech today on law and order.
</TEXT>
