<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 93 / Ecuador finally backs reforms for public sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND COLITT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   QUITO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE ECUADOREAN Congress has finally approved public sector reforms vital to
President Sixto Duran Ballen's economic programme, after nearly eight months
of deliberations.
A last-minute attempt by the opposition to reopen debate on the contentious
package - passed last week and now awaiting the president's signature - is
unlikely to win the necessary two-thirds majority.
The law is central to reducing the size of the public sector, privatising
state-owned enterprises, opening key sectors of the economy, and
deregulating numerous economic activities.
Its passage was hampered by the government's lack of a majority, its
unpopularity in the country and the slow procedures of Congress, which sits
for only three days a week.
Companies owned partly or entirely by the state may now be sold, liquidated,
or merged with other companies. Strategic sectors of the economy hitherto
reserved for the state - such as the petroleum industry, mining,
electricity, telecommunications and water utilities - will also be open to
the private sector through concessions, although the defence industry
remains reserved.
The liberalisation of foreign investment regulations in January and the
reform of the securities market in May have already made such areas easier
for foreign investors.
However, Congress restricted the use of debt-to-equity swaps for
privatisations in key sectors and introduced an anti-trust clause to prevent
state monopolies being superseded by private monopolies.
Despite having created the legal foundation for privatising much of the
public sector, the current administration may manage to tackle only a
fraction of the 167 enterprises involving public investment, nearly half of
which are entirely state-owned.
There is still considerable opposition to privatisation by bureaucrats and
workers in the bloated state apparatus, and the government will face strikes
and tough negotiations.
The new law has given the president executive powers to reform or eliminate
inefficient and superfluous enterprises. But more specific legislation will
be necessary to regulate private enterprises operating in new sectors. The
executive placed 26 bills before Congress last month. Without a clear
majority, it may take the government some time to get these passed.
'If we can privatise a few big companies during the term of this
administration, we will have accomplished something,' said Mr Carlos
Larreategui, under-secretary of public administration. The government's
strategy is to tackle the big and controversial companies first. The smaller
ones, he added, will then become easier.
Public entities will be trimmed of excess staff through offers of settlement
payments to employees who have worked in the same institution for at least
two years and who resign voluntarily.
The revenue from the sale of public entities will have to be reinvested in
education, health, housing and other basic services.
</TEXT>
