<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 93 / World Trade News: Boost for opponents of BAe's Taiwan
venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN and DENNIS ENGBARTH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, TAIPEI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TAIWANESE opponents of a joint venture deal with British Aerospace to build
regional jet aircraft in Taiwan scored a success yesterday when the minister
sponsoring the deal said he might quit as a director of Taiwan Aerospace
Corporation, BAe's joint venture partner.
Mr Yang Shih-chien, deputy minister of economic affairs, said: 'It would not
be bad to have a more detached position.' His statement comes a week after
the resignation of Mr Denny Ko, TAC's president and the man who signed the
original joint venture agreement with BAe in January 1993.
Opposition politicians, who had called for Mr Yang's resignation from TAC's
board, yesterday renewed their attacks on the proposed joint venture, Avro.
They accused BAe of not guaranteeing technology transfer for the development
of a new model, the RJX.
The deal is part of BAe's strategy to improve profitability - the RJ series
of aircraft, which would be built partly in Taiwan, loses money for the
company.
The latest attack and Mr Yang's statement will be the backdrop to a new
round of talks between BAe and Taiwan later this month.
These are aimed at finalising the arrangements for the transfer to Taiwan of
technology and development expertise, and outstanding legal issues.
But opposition politicians and bank lenders have attacked the joint venture
as politically, rather than commercially, inspired.
