<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 93 / EC stays on course for enlargement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUXEMBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Community yesterday said it was sticking to its optimistic
schedule of bringing Austria, Sweden, Finland and Norway into the Community
by January 1995, just as it became clear at ministerial negotiations in
Luxembourg that the hardest part of the enlargement talks has yet to begin.
EC foreign ministers said they expected the negotiations with the four
applicants to be concluded by next March at the latest, for entry by 1995.
They have called an extra ministerial session with the four for next month,
to try to make this date feasible. Privately, however, EC officials
acknowledge that dates may slip. A conclusion by March would in any case be
very tight, since all four countries have to hold referendums on entry.
'It's a question of political will,' one EC negotiator said, and of the
applicants 'defining a decent period of resistance' to EC demands, for fear
that their increasingly Euro-sceptical peoples will see their governments as
a push-over in the negotiations if they settle contentious issues too
quickly.
Sweden is so far top of the class, having closed 10 of the 29 negotiating
chapters for accession; Norway, which joined the negotiations some months
after the others started in February, has only settled seven chapters. The
areas agreed concern issues such as company law, social policy, and freedom
of movement for workers. They mark the conclusion of a second round in the
talks, after the four-month review of applicant country legislation
concluded in June.
In the third round, the Commission is expected to come up with draft
proposals to resolve the most difficult issues in the next four to six
weeks. All four want special regimes to continue paying lavish subsidies to
their Arctic and alpine farmers, and in the Scandinavian case, to finance
regional policies to keep their northern territories populated.
All four also want to retain restrictions on foreigners buying holiday homes
in their countries and to keep their generally higher environmental
standards, which the EC may argue could constitute barriers to trade.
Norway, in addition, has made clear it intends to keep control of its rich
energy and fisheries resources, while Austria wants to carry over unchanged
into its accession accord to the transit treaty regulating environmentally
the flow of EC trucks through its alpine passes, agreed for the European
Economic Area.
If all these issues are resolved, the 12 and the four still have to agree on
how the applicants fit into the foreign policy, security and home affairs
arrangements of Maastricht, and on how much they should pay into the EC
budget.
</TEXT>
<XX>
