<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 93 / Yeltsin purges political opponents: Emergency restrictions
on media provoke a public outcry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON and GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Boris Yeltsin yesterday purged opponents in Moscow and in the
regions amid a public outcry over emergency restrictions on the media and,
separately, allegations that arrested demonstrators had been severely
beaten.
Mr Yeltsin, who declared a week-long state of emergency in Moscow after the
army crushed an armed uprising by supporters of the parliament, sacked the
prosecutor-general, Mr Valentin Stepankov, and two regional governors.
He also postponed a meeting of regional leaders, who had been expected to
set up a new Federation Council, to give himself more time to purge disloyal
officials in the provinces. Restrictions on the media, including bannings
and censorship, caused a storm of protest and the resignation of Mr
Yeltsin's media aide, Mr Mikhail Poltoranin.
At least 150 people were killed in the two days of violence, according to Mr
Oleg Soskovets, first deputy prime minister. Separately it emerged that
1,500 people, rounded up after elite troops stormed the White House, were
being held in detention centres around Moscow.
Apart from the rebellion's top leaders, such as Mr Alexander Rutskoi, the
former vice-president, and Mr Ruslan Khasbulatov, the parliamentary speaker,
who were in Lefortovo jail, those in custody included deputies who had
stayed in the White House, as well as snipers and demonstrators who had
stormed the mayor's office and the television centre on Sunday night.
One of those detained and then released, Mr Boris Kagarlitsky, a well-known
writer and member of the Moscow city council, said yesterday that many
demonstrators and bystanders had been severely beaten to force confessions
while in police custody.
'We were handcuffed and beaten with Kalashnikovs to make us sign a
confession. We were not blindfolded, but told to face the wall, and if we
turned around we were kicked,' he said, adding that their official charge
was stealing a police car.
The deputies were finally released, one with a broken rib, when an
international human rights group learnt of their arrest and telephoned
police stations directly.
However, Mr Kagarlitsky, 35, said that at least two more deputies from the
Moscow city council were still being held.
'I was a dissident under Brezhnev and jailed for 13 months then. But I was
never beaten like that then,' he said.
Mr Yeltsin's onslaught also turned to the regions. According to his original
plan when he dissolved the Russian parliament two weeks ago, the Federation
Council was to become the un-elected upper chamber of a new parliament. It
was due to comprise the chiefs of the regional administrations and councils
in each of Russia's 88 regions.
But Mr Pyotr Philipov, a presidential aide, said Mr Yeltsin was now
considering whether to dissolve all councils. The aim would be to replace
them with new-style councils with less influence over the day to day running
of regional affairs.
Opposition political pro-communist parties, banned on Monday, yesterday
vowed to fight on, but claimed they would be prevented from registering for
the parliamentary elections.
The Russian Communist party, the largest of the parties, disputed that it
had been banned and insisted it would operate as normal.
More reports, Page 2;
Bonds, Page 31;
Currencies, Page 33;
World stocks, Page 39
'Only guaranteed freedom of speech can save the regime from degeneration and
arbitrary rule'
 - Part of a declaration by journalists of the liberal Sevodnya (Today)
newspaper, which was kept out of yesterday's edition by the new censors
Report, Page 2
</TEXT>
